1 WHEREAS, targeted investments in energy efficiency, building modernization,
2 on-site energy generation, and workforce training infrastructure can deliver lasting
3 reductions in operational costs to taxpayer-funded institutions and build the kind of
4 education-to-career pipelines that keep young Louisianans working and raising families in
5 the communities that raised them; and
6 WHEREAS, well-designed public-private partnerships, supported by targeted tax
7 incentives and financing tools, can put private capital to work, upgrading public facilities at
8 little or no up-front cost to taxpayers, multiplying every state dollar with private investment;
9 and
10 WHEREAS, such a program would direct its benefits to the rural and economically
11 distressed communities that need them most, invite corporate, industrial, and financial
12 institution investment on terms favorable to the public, and align workforce training with the
13 real and immediate needs of industry in this state; and
14 WHEREAS, the House of Representatives of the Legislature of Louisiana recognizes
15 the importance of accountability, measurable outcomes, and annual reporting to ensure
16 transparency and maximum public benefit.
17 THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the House of Representatives of the
18 Legislature of Louisiana does hereby urge and request Louisiana Economic Development
19 to conduct a comprehensive feasibility study on establishing a Louisiana Rural Community
20 Energy and Education Investment Program, including but not limited to all of the following
21 areas of study:
22 (1) Analysis of potential tax credit structures and other financing mechanisms
23 designed to attract private capital with minimal or no up-front cost to taxpayers.
24 (2) Identification of eligible investments in energy systems, energy-efficiency
25 improvements, building modernization, and workforce development infrastructure that are
26 most suitable for rural regions of this state.
27 (3) Rural prioritization mechanisms that target economically distressed parishes and
28 public institutions.
29 (4) Performance standards, projected cost savings for public entities, and economic
30 impact analysis.
